{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470928"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"82"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471196"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"82"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"82","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/82"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.15,0.24,0.26,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"82"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53984"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"82","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/82"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"82"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39455"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"157"},{"type":"tags","id":"1059"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7615"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16131"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44020"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53984"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA one-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother. She is distressed as earlier that morning her son had an episode where he fell to the ground and began having jerking movements for one to two minutes, then seemed to recover completely with normal behaviour for his age. His temperature at the time was 38.2\u00b0C. The boy has been unwell for the last three days with fevers up to 39\u00b0C, irritability, and decreased appetite. He has also had mild coryzal symptoms and swollen lymph nodes behind his ears. He is up to date with all of his vaccinations and received the MMR vaccine just over a week ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His weight is tracking along the 50th percentile for his age, and his height is between the 25th and 50th percentile. Neurological examination is unremarkable. He has a blanching maculopapular rash on his neck, trunk, and abdomen. His mother reports this is new, having first appeared within the last few hours, coinciding with the resolution of his fever.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A full blood panel should be obtained to rule out an infective or metabolic cause of his seizure","The boy has likely had a reaction to vaccination and he will require closer observation next time","Immediate transfer to hospital for investigation and management of possible meningitis","The boy may return to childcare despite the rash","The boy should have paracetamol prophylaxis next time he is ill"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child\u0027s presentation is consistent with roseola infantum, also known as exanthema subitum or sixth disease. It is a common, mild viral infection caused by human herpesvirus 6 (HHV-6) that typically affects infants and young children. The classic presentation includes high-grade fever for 3-5 days, followed by rapid resolution of the fever and appearance of a non-pruritic, blanching, pink maculopapular rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe boy may return to childcare despite the rash\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate advice. Once the rash of roseola infantum appears, the fever has typically resolved, and the child is no longer contagious. However, it\u0027s worth noting that some childcare centres may still be hesitant to accept a child with a visible rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA full blood panel\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary in this case. Simple febrile seizures, which this appears to be, do not require extensive investigation. They are defined as generalized seizures lasting less than 15 minutes that occur once in a 24-hour period in a febrile child aged six months to five years, with no signs of central nervous system infection or inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe boy has likely had a reaction to vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While febrile reactions can occur after vaccinations, they are rare. In this case, the timing and presentation are much more consistent with roseola infantum than a vaccine reaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate transfer to hospital\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary. If the boy had meningitis, one would expect him to be more unwell. His quick recovery and current well appearance make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe boy should have paracetamol prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended. Prophylactic use of antipyretics has not been proven to prevent febrile seizures. Paracetamol might be offered for symptom relief, but not as a preventive measure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that febrile seizures occur in about 15% of children with roseola infantum due to the high fever and the virus\u0027s ability to cross the blood-brain barrier. These seizures are typically self-limiting and do not require specific treatment beyond managing the underlying infection. Parents should be reassured about the benign nature of simple febrile seizures and educated about fever management and seizure first aid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The appearance of the rash associated with roseola infantum indicates that the patient is no longer contagious.","Febrile seizures are common in children with roseola infantum due to high fever.","Simple febrile seizures do not require extensive investigation or prophylactic antipyretics."],"references":["Mullins TB, Krishnamurthy K. Roseola Infantum (Exanthema Subitum, Sixth Disease).\u00a0In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448190/","Febrile Seizure. In: The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne Clinical Guidelines [online]. Cited 2022 Nov. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Febrile_seizure/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39455"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"82"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39455"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T14:52:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T19:38:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"82"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53984"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","n